<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO COOK</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jun 25 13:37:10 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
I respect your opinion and I thank you for your service in Vietnam. However, I disagree with you.<br><br>
When I returned from Vietnam, I was very outspoken against the war. No, I didn't have the inclination, nor the time to actually demonstrate against the war. But, I am still opposed to American involvement until this very day.<br><br>
What you fail to understand, in my opinion, is that the Civil War in Vietnam was between the communists - who were against any type of foreign domination and influence and were *nationalists* - and those in the South who represented a small, elite ruling class. As long as the Diem government played ball we supported it. It didn't matter that many Vietnamese in the South thought that Diem was despicable.<br><br>
The people who deserved our support the most were the working class and the peasantry of Vietnam. They felt alienated by the Diem Government. The Buddhists, likewise, were against the Diem regime. None were represented by the South Vietnamese government. <br><br>
The Viet Cong were South Vietnamese - not &quot;invaders&quot; from the North. The were widely supported in the countryside.<br><br>
If the cause of the South Vietnamese government was just, it would have prevailed. It would have been a cause that average South Vietnamese would have willingly given their lives for. We wouldn't have had to do the fighting for them.<br><br>
Many times I walked through villages in South Vietnam and saw indifferent villagers. We were never given a hero's welcome. We were not welcome.<br><br>
It was their war, not ours.<br><br>
As for the Chinese fighting in Vietnam, I don't dispute this. I am sure it happened. What I don't understand is your perception that it is ok for one side to have support from foreigners (the US), but that the other side shouldn't be allowed to have outside support.
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


